\title{Conducting External Reconnaissance With Osint}

\taxon{skill}

\tag{OSINT}

\tag{reconnaissance}

\tag{attack-surface}

\tag{footprinting}

\tag{passive-recon}

\meta{version}{1.0.0}

\meta{description}{Conducts external reconnaissance using Open Source Intelligence (OSINT) techniques to map an organization's external attack surface without directly interacting with target systems. The tester gathers information from public sources including DNS records, certificate transparency logs, search engines, social media, code repositories, and data breach databases to build a comprehensive target profile. Activates for requests involving OSINT reconnaissance, external footprinting, attack surface mapping, or passive information gathering.}

\subtree{
\title{Conducting External Reconnaissance with OSINT}
\subtree{
\title{When to Use}
\ul{
\li{Performing the initial reconnaissance phase of a penetration test to gather intelligence before active scanning}
\li{Mapping an organization's external attack surface to identify unknown or shadow IT assets}
\li{Collecting employee information, email formats, and organizational structure for social engineering campaigns}
\li{Identifying exposed credentials, leaked data, or sensitive documents published on the internet}
\li{Scoping the breadth of an organization's digital footprint prior to a red team engagement}
}

\p{\strong{Do not use} for stalking, harassment, or unauthorized surveillance of individuals. OSINT gathering must be conducted within the scope of an authorized engagement and comply with applicable privacy laws (GDPR, CCPA).}
}

\subtree{
\title{Prerequisites}
\ul{
\li{Written authorization to perform reconnaissance against the target organization}
\li{Dedicated research workstation with a VPN or Tor for anonymized queries when required}
\li{OSINT framework tools installed: Amass, theHarvester, Shodan CLI, Recon-ng, SpiderFoot}
\li{API keys for Shodan, Censys, SecurityTrails, Hunter.io, VirusTotal, and GitHub for enhanced results}
\li{Disposable email accounts for accessing services that require registration during research}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Workflow}
\subtree{
\title{Step 1: Domain and DNS Enumeration}
\p{Enumerate all domains, subdomains, and DNS records associated with the target:}

\ul{
\li{\strong{Root domain identification}: Start with the primary domain and identify all related domains through reverse WHOIS lookups on registrant name, email, and organization using \code{\startverb whoxy.com\stopverb} or \code{\startverb domaintools.com\stopverb}}
\li{\strong{Subdomain enumeration}: Run multiple tools for comprehensive coverage:}
\li{\code{\startverb amass enum -passive -d target.com -o amass_subs.txt\stopverb} for passive subdomain discovery from 40+ data sources}
\li{\code{\startverb subfinder -d target.com -all -o subfinder_subs.txt\stopverb} for fast passive enumeration}
\li{\code{\startverb crt.sh\stopverb} certificate transparency log queries: \code{\startverb curl -s "https://crt.sh/?q=\%25.target.com&output=json" | jq -r '.[].name_value' | sort -u\stopverb}}
\li{\strong{DNS record analysis}: Query for all record types: \code{\startverb dig target.com ANY\stopverb}, check for SPF, DKIM, DMARC records that reveal email infrastructure, and enumerate MX records to identify email providers}
\li{\strong{Zone transfer attempt}: \code{\startverb dig axfr @ns1.target.com target.com\stopverb} to check for misconfigured DNS servers}
\li{\strong{Consolidate results}: Merge, deduplicate, and resolve all discovered subdomains to IP addresses. Map IP addresses to ASN and hosting providers.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Step 2: Infrastructure and Service Discovery}
\p{Identify internet-facing infrastructure without directly scanning target systems:}

\ul{
\li{\strong{Shodan}: \code{\startverb shodan search "ssl.cert.subject.cn:target.com"\stopverb} to find all internet-facing services with TLS certificates for the target domain. Also search by organization name and IP ranges.}
\li{\strong{Censys}: Search for target's IP ranges and TLS certificates to identify services, technologies, and potential vulnerabilities indexed from internet-wide scanning}
\li{\strong{Cloud asset discovery}: Check for S3 buckets (\code{\startverb target-com\stopverb}, \code{\startverb target-backup\stopverb}, \code{\startverb target-dev\stopverb}), Azure Blob storage (\code{\startverb target.blob.core.windows.net\stopverb}), and GCP storage using tools like \code{\startverb cloud_enum\stopverb}}
\li{\strong{WAF and CDN identification}: Use \code{\startverb wafw00f target.com\stopverb} to identify web application firewalls and CDN providers that may mask the origin server IP}
\li{\strong{Historical data}: Use Wayback Machine (\code{\startverb web.archive.org\stopverb}) to find removed pages, old application versions, and forgotten endpoints}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Step 3: Email and Personnel Intelligence}
\p{Gather employee information and email addresses for social engineering preparation:}

\ul{
\li{\strong{Email harvesting}: \code{\startverb theHarvester -d target.com -b all -f harvest_results.html\stopverb} to collect emails from search engines, LinkedIn, and data sources}
\li{\strong{Email format identification}: Use \code{\startverb hunter.io\stopverb} to determine the email format (first.last, flast, firstl) and verify deliverability}
\li{\strong{LinkedIn reconnaissance}: Identify employees by department, particularly IT administrators, security team members, and executives. Note technologies mentioned in job postings and employee profiles.}
\li{\strong{Organizational chart}: Build an org chart from LinkedIn data to understand reporting structures, identify key personnel, and map departments}
\li{\strong{Social media analysis}: Review employee social media profiles for information about internal tools, technologies, office locations, badge photos, and security practices}
\li{\strong{Job postings}: Analyze current and historical job postings on the company career page and job boards for technology stack details, tools, and infrastructure information}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Step 4: Credential and Data Leak Analysis}
\p{Search for exposed credentials and sensitive data:}

\ul{
\li{\strong{Breach databases}: Check \code{\startverb haveibeenpwned.com\stopverb} API for breached email addresses associated with the target domain}
\li{\strong{Paste sites}: Search Pastebin, GitHub Gists, and similar paste sites for leaked credentials, configuration files, or internal documents}
\li{\strong{Code repositories}: Search GitHub, GitLab, and Bitbucket for:}
\li{\code{\startverb org:target "password"\stopverb}, \code{\startverb org:target "api_key"\stopverb}, \code{\startverb org:target "secret"\stopverb}}
\li{Use \code{\startverb trufflehog\stopverb} or \code{\startverb gitleaks\stopverb} for automated secret scanning across the target's public repositories}
\li{\strong{Document metadata}: Download publicly available documents (PDF, DOCX, XLSX) from the target website and extract metadata using \code{\startverb exiftool\stopverb} to reveal internal usernames, software versions, printer names, and file paths}
\li{\strong{Google dorking}: Use targeted search operators:}
\li{\code{\startverb site:target.com filetype:pdf\stopverb} for public documents}
\li{\code{\startverb site:target.com inurl:admin\stopverb} for admin panels}
\li{\code{\startverb site:target.com "index of /"\stopverb} for directory listings}
\li{\code{\startverb site:pastebin.com "target.com"\stopverb} for paste site mentions}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Step 5: Technology Stack Profiling}
\p{Identify the technologies, frameworks, and services used by the target:}

\ul{
\li{\strong{Web technology fingerprinting}: Use \code{\startverb whatweb target.com\stopverb} or Wappalyzer browser extension to identify CMS, frameworks, JavaScript libraries, analytics, and server software}
\li{\strong{SSL/TLS analysis}: \code{\startverb sslyze target.com\stopverb} or \code{\startverb testssl.sh target.com\stopverb} to identify cipher suites, protocol versions, certificate details, and cryptographic weaknesses}
\li{\strong{JavaScript analysis}: Download and review JavaScript files for framework identifiers, API endpoints, internal hostnames, and version strings}
\li{\strong{DNS-based service identification}: Review TXT records for service providers (e.g., \code{\startverb v=spf1 include:_spf.google.com\stopverb} indicates Google Workspace, \code{\startverb MS=msXXXXXX\stopverb} indicates Microsoft 365)}
\li{\strong{Mobile app analysis}: Download the target's mobile applications from app stores and analyze with \code{\startverb apktool\stopverb} (Android) or \code{\startverb frida\stopverb} for hardcoded URLs, API endpoints, and embedded credentials}
}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Key Concepts}
\pre{\startverb
| Term | Definition |
|------|------------|
| **OSINT** | Open Source Intelligence; intelligence collected from publicly available sources including websites, social media, public records, and government data |
| **Passive Reconnaissance** | Information gathering without directly interacting with target systems, leaving no footprint in target logs |
| **Active Reconnaissance** | Information gathering that involves direct interaction with target systems (scanning, probing) and may be logged |
| **Certificate Transparency** | Public logs of TLS certificates issued by certificate authorities, queryable to discover subdomains and infrastructure |
| **Attack Surface** | The sum of all points where an unauthorized user can attempt to enter or extract data from an environment |
| **Google Dorking** | Using advanced Google search operators to find sensitive information indexed by search engines that was not intended to be public |
| **Shadow IT** | Technology systems and services deployed by employees or departments without the knowledge or approval of the IT department |
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Tools & Systems}
\ul{
\li{\strong{Amass (OWASP)}: Comprehensive subdomain enumeration tool that combines passive sources, DNS brute-forcing, and certificate transparency log analysis}
\li{\strong{Shodan}: Internet-wide scanning database that indexes services, banners, and metadata for internet-connected devices, searchable by IP, domain, or organization}
\li{\strong{theHarvester}: OSINT tool for gathering emails, subdomains, hosts, employee names, and open ports from public sources}
\li{\strong{SpiderFoot}: Automated OSINT collection platform that queries 200+ data sources and correlates findings into a unified graph}
\li{\strong{Recon-ng}: Modular web reconnaissance framework with a database backend for organizing and cross-referencing discovered intelligence}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Common Scenarios}
\subtree{
\title{Scenario: Pre-Engagement Reconnaissance for a Red Team Exercise}
\p{\strong{Context}: A technology company has contracted a red team assessment. Before active testing begins, the team conducts passive OSINT to map the attack surface and identify potential entry points. The target is a SaaS company with 500 employees and a primary domain of techcorp.io.}

\p{\strong{Approach}:}

\ol{
\li{Enumerate 147 subdomains via Amass and crt.sh, including staging.techcorp.io, jenkins.techcorp.io, and vpn.techcorp.io}
\li{Shodan reveals a forgotten Elasticsearch instance on port 9200 with no authentication exposed to the internet}
\li{theHarvester collects 89 employee email addresses, revealing the format first.last@techcorp.io}
\li{GitHub search discovers a former developer's public repository containing a \code{\startverb .env\stopverb} file with AWS access keys}
\li{LinkedIn analysis reveals the company uses Okta for SSO, Jira for project management, and AWS for hosting}
\li{Google dorking finds a directory listing on docs.techcorp.io exposing internal architecture diagrams}
\li{Compile all intelligence into a reconnaissance report that feeds directly into the threat modeling and attack planning phases}
}

\p{\strong{Pitfalls}:}

\ul{
\li{Relying on a single subdomain enumeration tool and missing assets found by other tools using different data sources}
\li{Failing to check cloud storage services (S3, Azure Blob, GCP) for publicly accessible buckets}
\li{Not searching for credentials in public code repositories, which frequently yield immediate access}
\li{Conducting active scanning (port scans, vulnerability scans) during what should be a passive-only phase}
}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Output Format}
\pre{\startverb
## External Reconnaissance Report - TechCorp.io

### Attack Surface Summary
- **Domains discovered**: 3 (techcorp.io, techcorp.com, techcorpapp.com)
- **Subdomains enumerated**: 147 unique subdomains across all domains
- **Unique IP addresses**: 34 IPs mapped across AWS us-east-1 and us-west-2
- **Email addresses collected**: 89 valid corporate email addresses
- **Exposed services**: 12 internet-facing services identified via Shodan/Censys

### Critical Findings

**1. Unauthenticated Elasticsearch Instance**
- Host: 52.xx.xx.xx:9200 (elastic.techcorp.io)
- Indexed data: Application logs containing user session tokens and PII
- Source: Shodan search "ssl.cert.subject.cn:techcorp.io"

**2. AWS Credentials in Public GitHub Repository**
- Repository: github.com/former-dev/techcorp-scripts
- File: .env containing AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID and AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY
- Status: Keys appear active (not tested - out of scope for passive recon)

**3. Directory Listing Exposing Internal Documents**
- URL: https://docs.techcorp.io/internal/
- Contents: Architecture diagrams, network topology, runbooks
- Source: Google dork "site:techcorp.io intitle:index.of"

### Recommendations
1. Immediately rotate the exposed AWS credentials and audit CloudTrail logs
2. Restrict Elasticsearch access to internal networks or add authentication
3. Disable directory listings on docs.techcorp.io and audit all web servers
4. Implement GitHub secret scanning across all organization repositories
\stopverb}
}
}